<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-754-611  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 754 611.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>The Office  July 1989 v110 n1 p50(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>For desktop publishing: scanning expands its use. (includes arelated article on packaging desktop published products)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Kalow, Samuel Jay.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Copying technology has kept pace with advancements in printingtechnology.andP;  Scanning software can be used to edit, expand orreduce, rotate or manipulate an image to fit anywhere on the text,and the resulting image can be imported to the memory of thecomputer.andP;  Previously, the scanning rate had to be the same as theprinter rate, but conversion programs now allow an image to bescanned at half the picture elements per inch as the output rateof the printer.andP;  A wide variety of paper forms can be scanned andrecorded on a magnetic disk and reproduced by anall-points-addressable printer.andP;  The editing capabilities ofscanning software allow for faster implementation of changes instored forms.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Desktop PublishingScanningOffice AutomationCopyingBinding.andO;Feature:   illustrationcartoon.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>